ith techniques ranging from life-or-death escapes from an armed assailant to slapstick moves designed to please the crowd in public fencing matches. This translation, complete with all illustrations from the manuscript, makes the treatise accessible for the first time since the author's untimely death less than a year after its completion left his major work to be lost for generations. An extensive introduction, notes, and glossary analyze and contextualize the work and clarify its technical content. Jeffrey L. Forgeng is curator of Arms and Armor and Medieval Art at the Worcester Art Museum, and teaches as Adjunct Professor of History at Worcester Polytechnic Institute.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSwordplayvEarly works to 1800zGermany. 0aSwordsvEarly works to 1800. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArt of Swordsmanship.  aCombat.  aFighting.  aHans Lecküchner.  aMedieval.  aMiddle Ages.  aSwords.  aSwordsmanship.  aTechniques.  aText.  acombat arts.  afighting with swords.  ahistorical combat techniques.  ahistorical martial arts.  amartial arts manuscripts.  amedieval combat techniques.  amedieval fencing.  amedieval fighting.  amedieval swordsmanship.  amedieval texts.  asword techniques.  atechniques.1 aForgeng, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLecküchner, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045267?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045267/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete e